-I’ve found that strong onboarding docs behave more like product UX than reference material. Every page reduces uncertainty or it should not exist.
-
-**Short answer:** Developer onboarding docs work when they are executable, opinionated, and current. A new engineer should be able to follow one setup path, understand the system’s major components, identify code owners, and ship a small first change without hunting through Slack or asking for tribal knowledge. Docs fail when they are broad but unverifiable, duplicated across tools, detached from the real development environment, or silent about ownership and validation.
 
-## What good onboarding docs actually do
-
-I think teams over-focus on coverage and under-focus on sequence. Coverage sounds responsible. Sequence is what gets someone productive.
+Developer onboarding docs fail for a boring reason: they often document the system instead of documenting the path to a first useful change. I have seen teams keep a polished architecture wiki, a sprawling README, and a dozen Notion pages, then still leave a new engineer blocked on a missing secret, an unstated seed script, or a pull request process nobody bothered to write down.
 
-Microsoft’s [onboarding guide template](https://microsoft.github.io/code-with-engineering-playbook/developer-experience/onboarding-guide-template/) is useful because it quietly gets the order right: scope, contacts, team agreements, environment setup, project building blocks, resources. That order matters. A new engineer cannot reason about a service if they still do not know which repo matters, who the dev lead is, or how to run the app end to end.
+I think the core job of onboarding docs is narrower than most teams admit. They should help a new developer get the code running, make one safe change, and ship it with the fewest possible hidden decisions.
 
-My take is simple: onboarding docs should answer four questions in this exact order.
-
-1. What am I setting up?
-2. How do I run it safely?
-3. How is it organized?
-4. What should I change first?
-
-Anything that does not help answer one of those questions belongs later in reference docs, not in the onboarding path.
+**Short answer:** The onboarding docs that work are task-first. They include a short README, a discoverable `CONTRIBUTING.md`, a reproducible dev environment, one guided first task, and reference material separated from explanation. The docs that fail try to teach the whole system up front, hide contribution rules in chat, and leave setup to tribal knowledge. I would optimize for time to first merged change, not for documentation volume.
 
-The best onboarding docs also acknowledge that reading is not the end state. GitLab’s [frontend onboarding course](https://docs.gitlab.com/development/fe_guide/onboarding_course/lesson_1/) does something many teams skip. It ties setup, codebase navigation, and merge request creation to a deliberately tiny first contribution. That last step matters more than most teams realize. Setup without a first task produces false confidence. A first task reveals whether the environment, permissions, review flow, and docs all actually work.
-
-## Setup docs work when the environment is reproducible
-
-Broken setup docs are the fastest way to destroy trust in the rest of the onboarding experience. Once the first page is wrong, every later page feels suspicious.
-
-I have seen this pattern repeatedly. Someone writes a detailed local setup guide, dependencies drift, one secret name changes, a port conflict appears on macOS, and the page turns into fiction. New hires stop following the doc halfway through and start collecting fixes from chat threads and calendar calls. That is the moment tribal knowledge wins.
+## What onboarding docs are actually for
 
-GitHub’s [Introduction to dev containers](https://docs.github.com/en/codespaces/setting-up-your-project-for-codespaces/adding-a-dev-container-configuration/introduction-to-dev-containers) spells out why teams moved toward repository-defined environments. A `devcontainer.json` can define frameworks, tools, extensions, and forwarded ports for a project. The underlying [Development Container Specification](https://containers.dev/implementors/spec/) pushes the same idea further: development environments should be easy to use, create, and recreate.
+GitHub's guidance on repository READMEs is blunt: a README should tell people what the project does, why it is useful, how to get started, where to get help, and who maintains it. GitHub also says a README should contain only what developers need to get started using and contributing to a project, while longer documentation belongs elsewhere. That framing matters because it cuts against a common habit: treating the README as a dumping ground for every architectural thought the team has had.
 
-That is the difference between setup docs that work and setup docs that rot. Strong setup docs point to a tested artifact. Weak setup docs try to manually describe a machine.
+My take is that onboarding docs are not a knowledge archive. They are a flow control system for week one.
 
-A good onboarding setup section should include:
+That means I care less about whether the docs are comprehensive in the abstract and more about whether they remove the specific blockers a new engineer will hit in order:
 
-- One default path for getting the app running locally or in a cloud dev environment
-- Exact prerequisites with versions where versions matter
-- A verification step that proves the environment works
-- A recovery path for common failures
-- A note on what not to do, especially around production data, secrets, and destructive scripts
+1. Can I run the code?
+2. Can I tell whether it is healthy?
+3. Can I find a safe first change?
+4. Can I submit that change without annoying everyone?
 
-GitLab’s onboarding material is blunt in a way I respect. Lesson 1 points newcomers to the GitLab Development Kit, notes a [16 GB RAM](https://docs.gitlab.com/development/fe_guide/onboarding_course/lesson_1/) prerequisite, and says installation may take around 20 minutes or more. Numbers like that are small, but they set expectations honestly. “Set up the dev environment” is vague. “Plan for 16 GB RAM and a 20-minute install” is operational.
+Anything that does not help with one of those steps belongs later, lower, or elsewhere.
 
-## Architecture docs work when they explain shape, not every detail
+## A first successful contribution should shape the whole doc set
 
-New engineers do not need a full encyclopedia on day one. They need a map.
+Microsoft researchers studying onboarding at Microsoft interviewed 32 developers and 15 engineering managers, then validated the themes with a developer survey of 189 and a manager survey of 37. Their finding that matters here is simple: onboarding is shaped by tasks. Learning, confidence building, and socialization all happen through the work a newcomer is asked to do.
 
-Many teams confuse architecture documentation with completeness. That instinct creates giant internal pages nobody can hold in their head. A better goal is orientation. Which services matter? Which datastore is authoritative? Which queue carries side effects? Which external dependencies are critical? Which path does a request follow?
+Django's contribution tutorial gets this right. It does not start with a theory lecture about the whole framework. It walks a new contributor through a concrete path: install Git, clone the repo, set up a virtual environment, run the test suite, write a test, make a code change, run tests again, and submit a pull request. That is onboarding documentation doing its actual job.
 
-Microsoft’s template calls this section [Project Building Blocks](https://microsoft.github.io/code-with-engineering-playbook/developer-experience/onboarding-guide-template/). That label is better than “Architecture Overview” because it forces a practical explanation of components rather than a diagram dump.
+I rarely see commercial engineering teams structure internal onboarding this way. They usually start with architecture diagrams, service maps, and a reading list. New engineers end up "learning" for days without producing a single signal that their environment works or that they understand the contribution path. That is a documentation design bug.
 
-I prefer architecture docs for onboarding to include three things:
+## What works: five documents with distinct jobs
 
-1. A system map with the major services and data stores.
-2. A request walkthrough for one representative user action.
-3. Links to decision records for choices a new engineer will otherwise misread as accidental.
+I like onboarding doc sets that are small and opinionated. Diataxis is useful here because it separates tutorials, how-to guides, reference, and explanation instead of letting every page become an awkward hybrid. A tutorial teaches through a guided experience. Reference supports someone who is already doing the work. Explanation helps once the reader steps back and wants to understand why the system looks the way it does.
 
-Architectural decision records help here because they preserve the why. Teams love saying “the code is the documentation.” Code shows what exists. Code rarely shows why Redis was chosen over Postgres for one hot path, why a monolith still owns billing, or why a service boundary looks awkward because of an old compliance constraint.
+For developer onboarding, I want five pieces:
 
-A new hire can survive imperfect diagrams. A new hire usually cannot survive missing rationale.
+| Document | Job in onboarding | What it should contain |
+| --- | --- | --- |
+| README | Fast orientation | Product purpose, quick start, health check, where to get help |
+| CONTRIBUTING.md | Contribution contract | Branch strategy, test commands, PR expectations, review norms |
+| Reproducible environment doc | Remove machine drift | `devcontainer.json`, Codespaces, setup script, required secrets shape |
+| First task tutorial | Create confidence | One scoped change from clone to merged PR |
+| Reference set | Unblock later work | Service map, commands, env vars, ownership, runbooks |
 
-## Ownership docs matter more than teams admit
+That split sounds obvious when written down. Very few teams actually enforce it.
 
-Many onboarding guides talk about processes and skip one of the most practical questions a newcomer has: who can answer this without making me guess?
+GitHub helps if you meet it halfway. A `CONTRIBUTING.md` file is surfaced on the repository's `contribute` page, in the repository sidebar, and in the repository overview. Issue and pull request templates standardize what contributors include when they open work. Those are not cosmetic niceties. They lower the amount of guessing a newcomer has to do before asking for review.
 
-GitHub’s [CODEOWNERS documentation](https://docs.github.com/en/repositories/managing-your-repositorys-settings-and-features/customizing-your-repository/about-code-owners) is relevant here for more than pull request routing. A repository with clear ownership gives a new engineer a social map of the codebase. That is onboarding documentation, whether teams label it that way or not.
+## The reproducible environment is part of the docs
 
-I have seen engineers lose half a day figuring out whether a failing test belongs to platform, product, frontend infrastructure, or some long-gone team with a retired Slack channel. A current ownership map removes that friction immediately.
+Teams often talk about onboarding docs as if the environment setup is separate. I think that distinction is fake. A broken setup path is a broken onboarding document.
 
-Good onboarding docs should point to:
+The Dev Container spec defines `devcontainer.json` as the metadata required to configure a development container for a well-defined tool and runtime stack. GitHub Codespaces goes a step further with prebuilds. GitHub's own docs say repositories that take more than 2 minutes to create a codespace are likely to benefit from prebuilds because source code, dependencies, extensions, commands, and configuration can be prepared before the developer starts the environment.
 
-- `CODEOWNERS` or the equivalent ownership file
-- Team boundaries for major services or directories
-- The review path for risky changes
-- The escalation path for blocked setup, flaky tests, and production-impacting questions
+That is one of the clearest examples of documentation and platform design reinforcing each other. A setup guide that says "run these 14 steps" is weaker than a setup guide that says "open the repo in the standard dev container, verify the app with this one command, then continue."
 
-GitHub also notes that a `CODEOWNERS` file must stay under [3 MB](https://docs.github.com/en/repositories/managing-your-repositorys-settings-and-features/customizing-your-repository/about-code-owners) to be loaded. That detail is not central to onboarding, but it reveals something useful: ownership systems only help when they stay maintainable. Giant ownership maps with endless exceptions usually signal an org structure that nobody has cleaned up.
+I have seen onboarding docs collapse under tiny environment mismatches:
 
-## Single-source docs beat “helpful” duplication
+1. A seed step exists but is not mentioned.
+2. A secret is required but nobody documents the non-production value shape.
+3. A background worker must run alongside the web app.
+4. A migration needs local sample data that only one teammate remembers.
 
-I do not buy the argument that duplicate onboarding pages are harmless. Duplicate pages create forked truths, and new hires have no way to know which one is current.
+Every one of those is a docs problem, even if the immediate fix is tooling.
 
-GitLab’s [Shared Reality](https://handbook.gitlab.com/teamops/shared-reality/) page makes a strong point I agree with: documentation scales when there is a single source of truth and when people are trained to retrieve knowledge from it instead of relying on word of mouth. That sounds obvious. Very few engineering teams actually enforce it.
+## The README should stop early
 
-One of the most common briefs I get from developer tool companies is some version of this problem: “We have docs in the handbook, setup notes in Notion, architecture diagrams in Miro, ownership in GitHub, and everyone still asks the same onboarding questions.” That is not a writing problem alone. That is an information architecture problem.
+GitHub explicitly recommends keeping only the information necessary to get started in the README and moving longer material elsewhere. I agree with that more strongly than most teams do.
 
-The fix is usually not “write more.” The fix is:
+A long README is not automatically a useful README. GitHub also truncates README content beyond 500 KiB, which is an extreme case, but the real failure shows up much earlier. Nobody onboarding to a codebase wants to scroll through architecture philosophy, deployment edge cases, dependency policy, and roadmap commentary before learning how to boot the app.
 
-1. Choose the canonical location for each class of knowledge.
-2. Turn the onboarding page into an index with a strict sequence.
-3. Delete or redirect competing pages.
-4. Put freshness ownership on named people, not on “the team.”
+I would keep the README ruthless:
 
-GitLab’s framing around the speed of knowledge retrieval is the part many teams miss. Retrieval speed matters more than document count. A repo with five precise pages beats a knowledge base with fifty mostly-correct ones.
+1. What the repo is.
+2. What prerequisites exist.
+3. Which command starts the local environment.
+4. Which command proves the setup worked.
+5. Where contribution rules live.
+6. Where deeper docs live.
 
-## Research on onboarding tools points to the same gap
+That last point matters. GitHub supports relative links in Markdown, which makes it easy to route readers from the README into `docs/CONTRIBUTING.md` or another doc without breaking local clones. A good README is a dispatcher. It should not try to be the whole airport.
 
-Academic work on onboarding makes the same problem look bigger and more stubborn. The 2024 systematic literature review [Software Solutions for Newcomers’ Onboarding in Software Projects](https://arxiv.org/html/2408.15989v1) analyzed 32 studies and found that many onboarding barriers remain unaddressed by existing solutions. The paper also notes that newcomers face barriers around social interaction, previous knowledge, finding a way to start, documentation, and technical hurdles.
+## What doesn't work: docs that confuse study with work
 
-That matches what I see in practice. Teams often treat documentation as if it only has to transfer information. Real onboarding has to reduce ambiguity across tools, code, people, and process at the same time.
+Diataxis makes a distinction I wish more engineering teams took seriously: reference and explanation serve study, while tutorials and how-to guides serve action. Onboarding usually fails when teams hand a newcomer explanation and assume they have enabled action.
 
-The non-obvious insight for me is that onboarding docs fail less from lack of content than from poor linkage between content types. A setup guide without a first task is weak. A first task without ownership is weak. Ownership without a system map is weak. A system map without a validation path is weak.
+Here is the pattern I see over and over:
 
-Plenty of articles on developer onboarding docs list the standard categories: setup guide, architecture, API docs, coding standards, troubleshooting. That list is fine. The missing piece is connective tissue. New hires do not experience docs as categories. They experience them as a sequence of blockers.
+1. A new engineer gets an architecture document.
+2. The document explains why the system has seven services.
+3. None of it says which service to run first, which port should answer, or which test is the cheapest confidence check.
 
-## What usually fails
+That is excellent explanation and terrible onboarding.
 
-Weak onboarding docs have a predictable smell. I look for these failure modes first:
+Another common failure is hiding contribution rules in social channels. GitHub's docs recommend explicit contribution guidelines and templates because contributors should not have to infer how to open a good issue or a useful pull request. If a newcomer has to ask Slack how to title a PR, whether screenshots are required, or which test command reviewers expect, the repository is under-documented.
 
-### Static setup pages with no validation
+A third failure is giving newcomers a "starter task" that is not actually starter-friendly. Microsoft's onboarding study is useful here because it connects early tasks with confidence building. A first task should expose the workflow without forcing a tour through every sharp edge in the system. Fixing a typo in docs can be too shallow. Rewriting the auth middleware can be insane. The sweet spot is a small production change with a visible test and a real reviewer.
 
-A page that ends at “install dependencies and run the app” is incomplete. The guide should end with a success check. Can I log in? Can I hit one endpoint? Can I run one test suite? Can I seed safe sample data? A setup path without validation forces the newcomer to infer success.
+## The non-obvious part: onboarding docs should encode review culture
 
-### Architecture pages written for insiders
+The usual advice stops at setup and architecture. I think that is incomplete.
 
-Terms like “edge service,” “orchestrator,” or “core platform” mean nothing if nobody defines them in local context. Internal shorthand saves time for incumbents and burns time for newcomers.
+A new developer does not feel onboarded when the app boots. They feel onboarded when they can submit a change and predict what happens next. That means the docs need to capture review culture in concrete terms:
 
-### Missing first-task guidance
+1. What counts as a complete PR.
+2. Which tests are mandatory locally.
+3. How reviewers want context presented.
+4. Which labels or issue links are required.
+5. Which kinds of changes need screenshots, migrations, or rollout notes.
 
-GitLab gets this right by steering people toward a one-character change before expecting broader fluency. I think more teams should copy that. First tasks should be deliberately small, reversible, and documented. Large first tickets are onboarding debt disguised as ambition.
+GitHub's pull request templates exist for a reason. A template can force the repository to ask for risk, testing notes, linked issues, rollout impact, or screenshots every time. That does more for onboarding than another prose paragraph about engineering excellence.
 
-### Docs with no owner
+My article on [how to write a changelog developers actually read](/blog/how-to-write-a-changelog-developers-actually-read/) comes from the same instinct. Developers need information in the format that helps them act. Onboarding docs are no different.
 
-A page without a named maintainer is a page already drifting toward obsolescence. I would rather see a modest guide with a visible owner than an elaborate handbook section maintained by nobody.
+## A practical structure I would ship
 
-### Process docs detached from the real repo
+If I were cleaning up onboarding docs for an engineering team tomorrow, I would ship this structure first:
 
-If linting rules live in config files, link them. If the CI pipeline defines required checks, point to the actual pipeline. If your review process depends on code owners, show the file. High-level prose should summarize. Source-controlled artifacts should remain the ground truth.
+1. `README.md`
+   Contains repo purpose, quick start, one health check, links onward.
+2. `CONTRIBUTING.md`
+   Contains branch naming, local test expectations, PR shape, review and merge norms.
+3. `docs/first-change.md`
+   Contains one tutorial that ends with a merged pull request.
+4. `docs/development-environment.md`
+   Contains `devcontainer.json` or Codespaces path, local fallback, required services, secrets schema.
+5. `docs/reference/`
+   Contains commands, architecture map, environment variables, service ownership, runbooks.
 
-## The onboarding doc stack I would ship
+I would also wire in issue templates, a pull request template, and one clearly labeled starter issue with full reproduction steps.
 
-If I had to reduce onboarding docs to the minimum useful set for an engineering team, I would ship this stack:
+That kind of cleanup is the same editorial problem I solve in my [work page](/work): deciding which technical details belong in the fast path, which belong in reference, and which should stay out of the first-read experience entirely.
 
-1. A start-here page that sequences the entire experience.
-2. A reproducible environment doc tied to a dev container, codespace, or scripted setup.
-3. A system map with one request walkthrough.
-4. A codebase map that explains major directories and common patterns.
-5. An ownership page tied to `CODEOWNERS` or an equivalent source-controlled artifact.
-6. A first-task guide with validation and review expectations.
-7. A troubleshooting page for the five failures every new hire hits.
+## How I would judge whether the docs are good
 
-Everything else can branch from there.
+I would not ask whether the docs feel comprehensive. I would track whether a new engineer can do these things without synchronous rescue:
 
-That stack also maps cleanly to how I think about technical writing work for engineering-led companies. Teams do not need decorative documentation. They need pages that reduce time-to-first-useful-change. That is the standard I use for product docs, internal docs, and the kind of developer content I write for clients on [my work page](/work).
+1. Reach a running local environment.
+2. Verify that environment with one explicit check.
+3. Find a first task with clear scope.
+4. Open a pull request in the house style.
+5. Recover from one expected failure using the docs alone.
 
-Natural internal links help here too. Teams that care about developer trust should care about changelog quality for the same reason. A developer who cannot tell what changed will struggle during onboarding and long after it. I covered that in [my piece on changelogs developers actually read](/blog/how-to-write-a-changelog-developers-actually-read/). The same principle shows up in runtime systems as well: hidden operational context hurts adoption. My article on [agent harnesses as the infrastructure layer agents actually need](/blog/agent-harnesses/) gets at the same underlying problem from the software side.
+That last one matters more than teams think. Perfect-happy-path docs are easy to write. Useful onboarding docs include the first few failure states on purpose: bad credentials, missing seed data, stale containers, a required background worker, a common test failure. I trust onboarding docs a lot more when they admit where people actually get stuck.
 
 ## FAQ
 
-**What is the single most important onboarding document?**
+**Should onboarding docs live in the repo or in a wiki?**
 
-The setup path. Nothing else matters if a new engineer cannot run the system safely and confirm it works. Architecture docs, coding standards, and process notes all land better after the environment is real.
+I would keep the critical path in the repo. GitHub surfaces README and `CONTRIBUTING.md` directly, and those files stay versioned with the code they describe. Wiki or handbook material is fine for broader context, but the steps to run, test, and contribute need to live next to the repository.
 
-**Should onboarding docs live in the repo or in a handbook?**
+**How long should onboarding docs be?**
 
-I prefer a split. Repo-native artifacts should own setup, codebase structure, ownership, and validation steps. A handbook can own broader context such as org structure, communication norms, and cross-functional process. The onboarding page should link both in one sequence so the newcomer does not have to guess where to look.
+As short as the task allows. A strong onboarding doc set can still be large overall, but each page should do one job. I would rather have six focused pages than one 4,000-word page that mixes setup, architecture, policy, and history.
 
-**How long should onboarding docs be?**
+**Should the first task be a docs fix or a code change?**
 
-As short as possible while still letting someone complete the first useful change. I would rather ship a 700-word start-here page with accurate links than a 5,000-word handbook page that tries to explain the whole company.
+I prefer a small code change with a visible test. A docs-only task teaches almost nothing about the execution path, and a large feature teaches too much at once. A small bug fix, a validation tweak, or a narrow UI correction usually gives the right amount of exposure.
 
-**Should AI-generated code tours replace onboarding docs?**
+**Do architecture docs belong in onboarding at all?**
 
-Not yet, at least not on their own. Generated tours can help people navigate unfamiliar code, and the research on onboarding tools suggests real value in recommendation systems and guidance layers. Still, they do not remove the need for verified setup, current ownership, and an explicit first task. Generated summaries are an overlay, not the foundation.
+Yes, but later in the path. A newcomer needs enough system context to avoid breaking things, but not a full theory course before they can run the app. I would link architecture explanation after the first successful local run and before the first medium-sized task.
 
-**How often should onboarding docs be reviewed?**
+**What is the fastest high-leverage fix for weak onboarding docs?**
 
-Every time a public workflow changes, and on a fixed cadence anyway. GitLab’s handbook recommends at least monthly individual updates and periodic team audits for the single source of truth. That is a sensible baseline for any team that wants onboarding pages to stay trustworthy.
-
-Trust is the real output of onboarding documentation. A new engineer follows the first page, gets the system running, understands the map, ships a small change, and learns that the docs tell the truth. Once that happens, the rest of the codebase gets easier.
+I would add a first-change tutorial and tighten `CONTRIBUTING.md` before touching anything else. Those two pages usually expose the hidden assumptions in setup, testing, and review culture faster than a broad doc rewrite.
 
