-1. A system map with the major services and data stores.
-2. A request walkthrough for one representative user action.
-3. Links to decision records for choices a new engineer will otherwise misread as accidental.
+Research backs that up. A Microsoft case study on onboarding in software teams found that tasks shape learning, confidence, and socialization during onboarding, and 67% of the task items they analyzed led to learning. Another Microsoft study on remote onboarding during the pandemic found recurring friction around documentation, communication, asking for help, and building team connection. Poor docs do not just slow people down. They push uncertainty onto the new hire at the moment they have the least context.
 
-Architectural decision records help here because they preserve the why. Teams love saying “the code is the documentation.” Code shows what exists. Code rarely shows why Redis was chosen over Postgres for one hot path, why a monolith still owns billing, or why a service boundary looks awkward because of an old compliance constraint.
+## Setup docs need a guaranteed path, not a heroic path
 
-A new hire can survive imperfect diagrams. A new hire usually cannot survive missing rationale.
+I have seen plenty of onboarding docs that technically work if the stars align. A README says “run bootstrap,” a wiki page says “install dependencies,” and an internal thread says “ignore that error.” Teams mistake that pile for a process.
 
-## Ownership docs matter more than teams admit
+GitHub’s writeup on moving much of GitHub.com development to Codespaces captures the real problem cleanly. Their old local setup could get a new hire running in half a day, but local development stayed brittle enough that they had a `--nuke-from-orbit` option in the bootstrap script. Later, GitHub cut codespace creation from 45 minutes to 5 minutes, and then to about 10 seconds with prebuilds. Setup became less fragile because the environment became more reproducible.
 
