-GitHub’s [CODEOWNERS documentation](https://docs.github.com/en/repositories/managing-your-repositorys-settings-and-features/customizing-your-repository/about-code-owners) is relevant here for more than pull request routing. A repository with clear ownership gives a new engineer a social map of the codebase. That is onboarding documentation, whether teams label it that way or not.
+I want an onboarding doc to answer these setup questions explicitly:
 
-I have seen engineers lose half a day figuring out whether a failing test belongs to platform, product, frontend infrastructure, or some long-gone team with a retired Slack channel. A current ownership map removes that friction immediately.
+- Which environment is the default one for the team right now?
+- Which commands should I run, in order?
+- What credentials do I need before I start?
+- What success check proves the environment works?
+- Which errors are common enough to document up front?
 
-Good onboarding docs should point to:
+Anything beyond that belongs in linked reference docs. Setup pages should optimize for first success, not full system understanding.
 
-- `CODEOWNERS` or the equivalent ownership file
-- Team boundaries for major services or directories
-- The review path for risky changes
-- The escalation path for blocked setup, flaky tests, and production-impacting questions
+## Good onboarding docs choose the first task on purpose
 
-GitHub also notes that a `CODEOWNERS` file must stay under [3 MB](https://docs.github.com/en/repositories/managing-your-repositorys-settings-and-features/customizing-your-repository/about-code-owners) to be loaded. That detail is not central to onboarding, but it reveals something useful: ownership systems only help when they stay maintainable. Giant ownership maps with endless exceptions usually signal an org structure that nobody has cleaned up.
+Managers often say they want a new engineer to “pick up something small.” Small is not a useful criterion on its own. A tiny task can still be terrible for onboarding if it touches obscure tooling, depends on unwritten history, or teaches nothing about how the team ships code.
 
-## Single-source docs beat “helpful” duplication
+The Microsoft onboarding case study surfaced three broad strategies: simple-to-complex, priority-first, and exploration-based. Simple-to-complex worked best for junior engineers because it built confidence gradually. Exploration-based work suited more experienced engineers when the team wanted broader discovery. Priority-first could work on high-pressure teams, but it raised the odds of low confidence if support was weak.
 
-I do not buy the argument that duplicate onboarding pages are harmless. Duplicate pages create forked truths, and new hires have no way to know which one is current.
+My take is simple: onboarding docs should encode the simple-to-complex path unless the team has a strong reason not to. A good onboarding page should link to a first task with these traits:
 
-GitLab’s [Shared Reality](https://handbook.gitlab.com/teamops/shared-reality/) page makes a strong point I agree with: documentation scales when there is a single source of truth and when people are trained to retrieve knowledge from it instead of relying on word of mouth. That sounds obvious. Very few engineering teams actually enforce it.
+- touches the real code path, not a toy project
+- goes through the full workflow from branch to review to merge
+- has a fast feedback loop
+- teaches one core team convention
+- carries low blast radius
 
-One of the most common briefs I get from developer tool companies is some version of this problem: “We have docs in the handbook, setup notes in Notion, architecture diagrams in Miro, ownership in GitHub, and everyone still asks the same onboarding questions.” That is not a writing problem alone. That is an information architecture problem.
+One of the better patterns I have seen is “fix one safe thing and ship it.” A typo in a user-facing string, a small test repair, a docs-linked code fix, or a noncritical UI edge case often works better than a large backend task marked “easy.” Shipping matters because it converts onboarding from passive reading into proof that the whole system works.
 
-The fix is usually not “write more.” The fix is:
+## Architecture pages are useful later than teams think
 
-1. Choose the canonical location for each class of knowledge.
-2. Turn the onboarding page into an index with a strict sequence.
-3. Delete or redirect competing pages.
-4. Put freshness ownership on named people, not on “the team.”
+Teams love starting onboarding docs with system architecture. I understand why. Senior engineers want new hires to appreciate the shape of the system. Writers want to be thorough. Founders want their design decisions preserved.
 
