+## Setup docs need a guaranteed path, not a heroic path
 
-A new hire can survive imperfect diagrams. A new hire usually cannot survive missing rationale.
+I have seen plenty of onboarding docs that technically work if the stars align. A README says “run bootstrap,” a wiki page says “install dependencies,” and an internal thread says “ignore that error.” Teams mistake that pile for a process.
 
-## Ownership docs matter more than teams admit
+GitHub’s writeup on moving much of GitHub.com development to Codespaces captures the real problem cleanly. Their old local setup could get a new hire running in half a day, but local development stayed brittle enough that they had a `--nuke-from-orbit` option in the bootstrap script. Later, GitHub cut codespace creation from 45 minutes to 5 minutes, and then to about 10 seconds with prebuilds. Setup became less fragile because the environment became more reproducible.
 
-Many onboarding guides talk about processes and skip one of the most practical questions a newcomer has: who can answer this without making me guess?
+That lesson matters even if you are not using Codespaces. Setup docs work when they describe one supported path in painful detail. Setup docs fail when they describe three maybe-paths and let the new engineer guess which one the team actually uses.
 
-GitHub’s [CODEOWNERS documentation](https://docs.github.com/en/repositories/managing-your-repositorys-settings-and-features/customizing-your-repository/about-code-owners) is relevant here for more than pull request routing. A repository with clear ownership gives a new engineer a social map of the codebase. That is onboarding documentation, whether teams label it that way or not.
+I want an onboarding doc to answer these setup questions explicitly:
 
-I have seen engineers lose half a day figuring out whether a failing test belongs to platform, product, frontend infrastructure, or some long-gone team with a retired Slack channel. A current ownership map removes that friction immediately.
+- Which environment is the default one for the team right now?
+- Which commands should I run, in order?
+- What credentials do I need before I start?
+- What success check proves the environment works?
+- Which errors are common enough to document up front?
 
